# UI/UX and design hierarchy

Layout, copy, and motion should **minimize cognitive load** — users should rarely ask “what do I do here?”

Document your app’s visual language (colors, spacing, typography) in project docs or design tokens so new UI stays consistent.

## Visual hierarchy

- **Spacing:** Use a consistent rhythm — with NativeWind, prefer utilities like `gap-*`, `p-*`, `m-*`, `px-*`, `py-*` instead of one-off magic numbers when building new UI.
- **Contrast:** Do not rely on font size alone; use **weight** and **color tone** to show importance. Ensure text meets contrast on tinted or saturated backgrounds (avoid low-contrast gray on strong fills).
- **Labels:** Prefer **icons + layout** to explain affordances; use short labels only when ambiguity remains. Pair icons with `accessibilityLabel` for screen readers.

## Usability

- **Self-evident:** Primary actions read as **buttons** (clear tap target); navigation affordances read as **tabs or links** (underline, icon + weight).
- **Navigation:** Follow the **Expo Router** file tree under `app/`. Back affordances and return paths should be obvious.
- **Forms:** Prefer **default** choices to the most helpful option; use progressive disclosure (sheets, steps) instead of long single pages when possible.

## Styling: NativeWind first (when the project uses it)

- **New UI:** Prefer **`className`** and your design tokens / Tailwind utilities. Avoid ad-hoc hex when a token or utility already exists.
- **Legacy:** When editing older `StyleSheet`-based components, migrate toward `className` where practical in the same change, without unrelated large refactors.

## Haptics

Prefer a **small shared helper** (e.g. `src/utils/haptics.ts`) wrapping `expo-haptics` so feedback is consistent:

| Kind | Typical use |
|------|----------------|
| Success / strong positive | Milestones, completed actions |
| Light | Toggles, light confirmation |
| Warning | Destructive paths, errors |
| Selection | Tabs, segmented controls, pickers |

## Motion (Reanimated)

Prefer **`react-native-reanimated`** for motion:

- Entering / exiting: `FadeInDown`, `FadeInUp`, `FadeInRight`, `FadeOutUp` on Reanimated `Animated.View`.
- List / layout: `Layout.springify()` where items reorder or resize.
- Values: `withSpring`, `withTiming`, `useSharedValue`, `useAnimatedStyle`.

Avoid **`LayoutAnimation`** in **new** code when Reanimated can cover the case; prefer Reanimated for predictable, interruptible animations.

## testID (E2E)

Expose **`testID`** on interactive controls (pressable, text input, switch) for Maestro or similar. Use a stable convention, for example:

```
{domain}:{component}:{action}
```

Examples: `home:add-button:press`, `settings:theme-select:change`.

## Accessibility

For new or heavily touched interactives, set at least:

- `accessibilityRole` (`button`, `link`, `switch`, …)
- `accessibilityLabel` (localized via your i18n layer where possible)

## Component placement

| Scope | Path (typical) |
|--------|----------------|
| Feature-only | `src/features/{domain}/components/` |
| Shared (2+ domains) | `src/components/` |
| One screen | `src/screens/{Screen}/components/` |

## Copy and i18n

Route **user-visible** strings through your i18n solution (e.g. `react-i18next`). See [.cursor/skills/add-i18n-key/SKILL.md](../skills/add-i18n-key/SKILL.md).
